#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Plugin SessionStart bootstrap — injects the rules-as-tests entry-point context so the
# using-rules-as-tests skill auto-triggers without a manual Skill invocation.
# Invoked via run-hook.cmd from plugin/hooks/hooks.json (matcher: startup|clear|compact).
# @cc-only-rationale: SessionStart stdout-injection is a CC-native fire-point with no portable
#   equivalent that fires at the same moment. Off-CC (OpenCode et al.) the using-rules-as-tests
#   skill is read on demand instead — the accepted degradation documented in S7
#   (.opencode/INSTALL.md) / dual-implementation-discipline.md §3.
# spec: docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-22-cc-plugin-packaging-design.md §3 (#4, ADAPT of using-superpowers)
#
# SessionStart contract: plain stdout is injected into the session context by Claude Code.
# Keep it short — progressive disclosure: the directive lives here, the full protocol in the skill.
set -uo pipefail

# Self-resolve our own dir (plugin-data); prefer the plugin root CC provides.
SCRIPT_DIR="$(cd "$(dirname "$0")" && pwd)"
PLUGIN_ROOT="${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT:-$(cd "$SCRIPT_DIR/.." && pwd)}"

cat <<BOOTSTRAP
[rules-as-tests plugin — session bootstrap]
This repo has the rules-as-tests plugin: turn every codebase convention into an executable
artifact that fails at the earliest reachable channel (edit-time → pre-commit → pre-push → CI
→ production). Thesis: documents lie; tests don't.

Before responding or acting — even before clarifying questions — invoke the relevant skill if
there is even a ~1% chance it applies:
  • using-rules-as-tests — the entry point: how to find/use these skills + the instruction ladder.
  • rules-as-tests — the 5-layer enforcement methodology (lint/CI/hooks, architecture, meta-tests,
    spec-by-example, mutation, living docs); trigger on any "make my code resist AI drift" ask.
Invoke via the Skill tool (do not Read the skill file to "use" it).

Instruction priority: this project's own CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md / direct user requests WIN over
the plugin's skills, which win over default behaviour. The plugin supplies discipline; the repo
stays in control.

Honest boundary: this plugin delivers the SOFT layer (skills/agents/session hooks). The HARD
layer (git hooks + CI that fail the build) is opt-in via /rules-as-tests:install-enforcement —
a plugin never silently mutates your git/CI.

Skills live under: ${PLUGIN_ROOT}/skills/
[/rules-as-tests plugin]
BOOTSTRAP
